[2]It was an inverted sesquiplane with a biplane tail and two engines mounted in a push-pull configuration within a common nacelle mounted on struts in the interplane gap above the fuselage.
[4]Established as a separate service in 1923, the Regia Aeronautica relied upon World War I-vintage Caproni Ca.3 bombers, and a replacement was soon sought.
[6]Bombs were carried on external racks on the fuselage sides.Ca.73s remained in frontline service until 1934, and from 1926 onwards participated in Italy's military actions in North Africa.
